I’m correcting for my overemphasis on the possibility of an approval rating under 38%. Looking at past presidents, that kind of rate is nearly unheard of, save Jimmy Carter. Given some or the similar economic challenges Biden faces though—particularly inflation—I can’t discount it entirely.

He just barely dipped below 38 back in July, and hasn't been above 46 since September 2021. Currently at 42.1. I think it would take something very dramatic (and unpredictable) for him to depart the 38-46 range in the next seven weeks.

His current presidential approval rating is 41.6 percent. The mid-term elections were contested and Republicans won the house. This likely means more gridlock in Congress, and also reported investigations into Hunter Biden and the withdrawal from Afghanistan. These investigations are likely to reduce his overall approval as unfavorable news comes out, whether it's fact-based or media spin.

From looking at the approval line graphs of the other presidents at this phase of their presidencies, it seems like roughly a coin flip whether Biden's approval rises or falls from here.
